by maura_mango

“You still haven’t told me where you’re from.” Tony had said.

“I’m from a small town called Gulmira. It’s actually a nice place,” Yinsen replied, a little wry in his natural tone.

"Got a family?

"Yes, and I will see them when I leave here. And you Stark?”

Tony thought of his parents. “No.”

“No. So, you’re a man who has everything, and nothing.”

Ten years later and those words still resonated deep within him. He was the man who had everything, and nothing.

(AKA Tony reflects on the life he’s been blessed with, bc this man deserves to be happy goddammit)

summary: what did you think of the last issue of no road home?
question: what did you think of the last issue of no road home?
answer:
I’m easy to please as much as I like to complain/nitpick when it comes to comic-related media, and while I do have my personal nitpicks, I thought the last issue was satisfying. Nyx was defeated in a way that made sense for her OP powerkit (in a ‘metabattle’?). Wanda and Vision had more of that much needed, overdue, but better than never closure on the status of their relationship. Happy Vision that’s drawn in a more wholesome instead of creepy flair always makes me happy. I obv like my #edge, but I like my unapologetically light triumphing over darkness cheese just as much, and I think this was a place for the latter especially. Also loved the Starlin and retro throwbacks. Loved the meta-Billy cameo. Loved the platonic hand-holding in lieu of, yanno the ‘sparks’ that were teased. ;; Would definitely pick up a physical copy.

Also did anyone else notice this Shi’ar looking dude sitting on air:

body:
Pairing: Clint Barton x Romanov!Reader

Warning: Language. Lies. Arguing.

Everyone has secrets. Especially the Romanov sisters. When you end up in a sticky situation you find yourself at the gate of Avengers Compound, looking for your sister, Nat. But little did you know your past was on the other side of the gate as well.
Clint Barton, he broke your heart and destroyed you, years ago. Tricks and secrets are a game you and your sister are well trained in, and you’re out to make Clint jealous. Payback is only fair, right? But Clint’s done playing games, yours and your sisters. Truth is coming out and you can’t stay away from Clint.

Malen’ kiy – Little One

“Christ Y/N. Alex? Of all people?” Nat starts towards you. “How did you end up on his hit list?” She throws her hands up. You match each of her step with a backwards one. The two of you slowly circling the massive living room.

“He’s a slumlord, Natalia.” You explain. “A girl I worked with. He was giving her a hard time. She’s got two kids, and he jacks up her rent when she refuses him.” You continue stepping backwards, as she continues towards you.

“What did you do?” She shakes her head, quickening her steps. You slip around the couch, and the coffee table.

“I beat on him. A little.” You roll your eyes. You hear Clint snort softly, irritation flares in you.

“A little?” Nat pauses, squinting at you.

“Well sadly I let him live.” You admit, your free hand waves down you emphasizing your beating.

“So hot.” One smirks, grinning. You wink at him, a small smile on your lips. He’s dark colored, with the friendliest grin, and pretty brown eyes.

“How did you end up beat up by his goons?” Nat huffs, folding her arms over her chest.

“Well clearly letting him live, was where I went wrong.” You snort. “They were in my apartment, waiting for me.” You wave your hand.

“I’m going to kill him.” She grinds out.

“I tried. He’s like cockroach.” You shrug.

“What’s the address?” The one with greying dark hair speaks up, everyone glances over at him.

“Why?” Your head tips.

“He’s going to buy it out from under Alex.” Nat sighs, shaking her head.

“Or did you want to kick him off the roof?” He smirks at her.

“Tony I will kick you off the roof.” She warns him, he blows her a kiss.

“Still violent as ever.” You smirk. From the corner of your eye you see Clint smirk, your hand balls into a fist.

“Nat.” A dark haired girl looks at your sister, who glances from you to her. “Perhaps introductions?” She nods. Your sister sighs.

“Right, fine.” She waves her hand. “Everyone this is my sister, Y/N.” She shakes her head, clearly annoyed you’d gotten yourself into trouble.

“I’m Wanda.” The dark haired girl smiles. She’s friendly, pretty and has a red hue in her eyes.

“She’s a friend.” Nat smirks at you, sensing your hesitation at her accent.

“How about Chinese and swapping stories. Clearly you have many, many secrets.” Tony smirks at Nat.

“I’ll kill you with a chop stick, Stark.” She warns.

“I’ve actually seen her do that.” You nod.

“Oh look who’s talking.” Nat gaps at you. “A spoon.” She lifts a brow.

“It was the only thing within reach!” You throw your hand up.

“Hot.” Peter smirks.

“So cutlery should be kept from the two of you?” The tall blonde chuckles. You and Nat smirk at him.

“Sure Rogers if that makes you feel safe.” Nat shrugs.

“I don’t know how much I like there being two of them.” The dark one looks around nervous.

“Fury used to say the same thing.” Clint snorts, pushing off the wall, he heads into the kitchen. You have to resist the dirty look you want to give him.

“Y/N meet. Steve Rogers. Peter Parker. Sam Wilson. Tony Stark and Bucky Barnes.” Nat introduces you.

“Nice to meet you.” You smile.

“And you remember Clint.” Nat waves her hand at her best friend and your nemesis. The rest of you heading into the kitchen as well.

“Hard to forget.” You reply, your tone cold. Nat flicks you in the shoulder.

“Likewise.” Clint mutters into a coffee mug.



——————-



“Why keep her a secret from us?” Steve asks, as Nat passes him the duck sauce. You’d done the introduction, allowed medical to look you over, and been convinced to join them for dinner.

“It’s complicated.” Nat sighs.

“No, it’s not.” You pop a veggie in your mouth.

“Y/N.” She warns you. You sat between Steve and Peter. Clint sat directly across from you, the two of you kept meeting eyes, it was getting on your last nerve.

“Yeah,” you nod “that threatening growl stopped scaring me years ago.” You smile at her.

“She’s not scared of Nat, she must be bullet proof.” Peter whispers at Tony.

“She wouldn’t shoot her poor little sister.” You blow her a kiss.

“No, I would.” She gives you a look.

“You’re so pretty when you get annoyed.” You grin at her.

“Now do you see why I kept her a secret?” Nat huffs looking around.

“No.” Steve, Peter, Tony and Sam reply at the same time. You smile, popping another veggie into your mouth.

“She wanted me to have a normal life. One outside the Red Room Academy training.” You nod, picking up your drink.

“So,” Buck looks from Nat to you “you were in the Red Room as well?” He asks softly. Something in his blue eyes is familiar, like a far off memory you couldn’t place.

“Another Madame success story, in the flesh.” You nod.

“Hush, Malen’ kiy.” Nat points a chop stick at you.

“So did you have a normal life?” Steve looks over, a small smile on his lips.

“Nope.” You reply. Nat gives you a look, one you can’t place. “I’m always running from one thing or another. Never good enough.” You shrug. Clint stiffens, swallowing hard.

“Never good enough?” Wanda tips her head.

“Long story. Another life.” You smile softly at her.

“What are you going to do now?” Sam asks watching you. You chew slowly, swallowing.

“Probably disappear again.” You shrug. “Reinvent myself.” Clint and Nat exchange a look, something you hadn’t expected from the two of them. Panic.

“Why,” Nat speaks up “don’t you stay tonight?” She asks. “We can talk it over in the morning.” She offers. You shrug.

“Couldn’t hurt I guess.” You nod. Covering your mouth as you yawn.

“Take my room.” Nat adds. “I’ll crash with Buck, tonight.” She glances at the dark haired man. When your eyes meet him that familiar feeling creeping up your spine.

“Okay.” You nod. “Thanks.” You stand up with your empty plate.

“Clint, take her upstairs, will you?” Nat looks at her best friend. You look at Nat than Clint, a nervous twinge crawls down your spine.

“No, no, it’s fine.” You shake your head, stepping around to get free. “I’ll make it on my own.” You nod. “I’m a big, tough girl.” You flex. “I tie my own shoes even.” You remind your sister.

“I’ll walk you.” He stands up. Taking your plate with his. “No problem.” He nods.

“Oh dandy.” Your mouth fills with a sour taste as you grab the duffle you packed before you split.
